Now debuting in her 19th season</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/28/02 12:04:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=287.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_bigsmile.gif" align=absmiddle>  One month assessment</span><hr size=1> The good:<br>
<br>
Zone populations are lighter than a regular blue server, but in the lower levels there are still plenty of people.  I suspect you have to be very agressive early on if you are a group dependant class and came here alone.  Make friends, join a guild etc. I have a permanent partner, and I play a soloable class.  I don't mind somewhat empty zones.  I would hate to be a cleric or rogue on FV, if I was anti-social at all.  The quiet is incredible.  No OOC spam, no auctions in every zone.  The world &quot;feels&quot; emptier, even if 20 people are in the zone with you.  I think this contributes to realism and RP environment.  I am much more inclined to try and talk to players I meet, and rp as well.  I also like camping something level specific and not having to wait for A_druid_Farmer_124567 to finish the camp before taking it over.  Languages are alot of fun.  None of my other characters ever learned any other languages.  My partner and I are very strict about it.  Every time we zone (and with melee only bind spots, its often) and every hour within a zone (we use a timer) we train a point of language.  At lvl 20 we have mastered elvish and dark elvish.  She has learned 50 points of Barbarian, we are feeble in 4 or 5 tongues and have a point at least in everything else.  As we travel and expand our horizons we are able to understand more and more people.  I think it helps in immersion, though perhaps lvl*10 might be more appropriate for language...<br>
<br>
The indifferent:<br>
<br>
TLC definately favors the experienced players.  I have a few servers and a few high level characters under my belt.  I play with my rl partner.  She plays a monk and I a Northman shaman.  Between us we have to camp about 15 things in the next 5 levels.  Without foreknowledge, either from experience, or from spoiler sites, you will find yourself buying alot of TLC items later for quests (monk epic for example starts at lvl 1).  Also the level specific camping has slowed us down considerably.  While leveling is not as important to me as it has been before, we do play alot less as well than on previous servers (average of 20 or so hours a week vs. 40-50 or even more gah!), I will not feel complete as a shaman until lvl 35 (pet at 34 and no more spell book!).  There are also alot more interesting things to do in the midlevels, and I have expensive hobbies...  trying to master tailoring, smithing, baking, brewing, pottery, and alchemy will easily cost me 25K throughout my career, so the better loot at higher levels is enticing me....  The market... Wow, it is rare indeed to buy in game without first hitting the boards here.  This is ok, but perhaps only a few percent of players actually comes here.  Maybe the bazaar will fix this up.<br>
